One America, Two Peoples
New York — As I write this article, officials across the United States are still counting the votes from the 2020 presidential election.
Once the statistical results are finalized, recounts and legal challenges are sure to follow.
This was to be expected in this highly competitive election with record voter turnout.
Only American citizens can vote to elect the President of the United States, but this choice affects people all over the country.
If it's too early to determine the election results, then it's not too early to reflect on the implications of this election for the world's most powerful country.
From a positive perspective, the United States remains a strong democratic nation.
Despite the practical limitations related to the pandemic, voter turnout remained high.
This process seems to be proceeding as planned.
Moreover, violent incidents are rare.
The court is investigating the U.S. Postal Service's decision, which appears to be motivated by political considerations, hindering the delivery of ballots from regions where the expected vote count is primarily from Democratic voters.
The current U.S. President, Trump, announced his victory without any basis on Tuesday evening, receiving little response. His request to halt the vote counting (at least in the states where he was leading) seemed to be ignored.
However, it is concerning that the divisions among American voters remain significant.
The votes for the two candidates were almost equal.
It is not surprising that this division is likely to lead to a split in the government.
If the current trend continues, the Democratic Party will win the White House and continue to control the House of Representatives, while the Republican Party will continue to control the Senate.
The governor's seat and state legislative seats are almost evenly split between the two parties (with the Republican Party having a slight advantage).
The Democrats' anticipated "blue wave" did not materialize.
Biden is very likely to win the popular vote by a significant margin, securing around four to five million votes out of nearly 160 million.
However, Republicans held many Senate seats that many had predicted would flip, while Democrats actually lost seats in the House.
This outcome does not come from strong authorization, nor does it stem from political adjustments.
Trump's poll numbers are excellent, with 5 million more votes than in 2016, making him the second-highest vote-getter among all U.S. presidential candidates in history and surpassing any previous winner.
Notably, this occurred against the backdrop of a new record high in daily COVID-19 cases, exceeding 100,000, and over 1,000 deaths.
Just as the consequences of his government's inadequate handling of the outbreak were becoming most severe, nearly half of the voters turned to support him.
Even if Trump loses, which seems very likely, he will still have significant influence, especially if he continues to stay in the public eye (which also seems likely).
Even if he himself does not run, he is likely to have a significant influence on the selection of the Republican nominee in the 2024 presidential election.
The Republican Party would be very different from the party of President Bush or Reagan.
Trumpism — a form of modern American populism — will remain a powerful force.
Unsurprisingly, despite Trump's inability to present any evidence, he desperately tried to portray himself as virtuous and upright, attempted to undermine the legitimacy of the election results, and accused there being fraudulent activities.
Many of his supporters will reject the legitimacy of Biden's presidency.
Trump is very likely to never admit defeat and certainly will not attend the swearing-in ceremony of his successor.
As Will Rogers once said, Trump has never encountered a norm he couldn't break.
Americans are increasingly living in different worlds.
They classify themselves into different communities and regions based on similar viewpoints.
And each world tends to watch its own cable television channels, listen to its own radio stations and podcasts, and visit its own websites.
The absence of a national civic curriculum has facilitated the differentiation among people from different generations.
It is worth emphasizing that the division of nations is not typically along economic lines in most cases.
People from all social strata voted for both candidates, and the voting patterns by population, gender, and race were not as one-sided as many had predicted.
Their disagreement mainly lies in the remedial measures.
Educational attainment is clearly an indicator of political orientation, as is geographic location. Republican voters tend to reside in suburban and rural areas, while Democratic voters are more likely to live in metropolitan regions.
However, the role of culture in American politics may be greater than any other factor.
In fact, foreign policy seems to be of less importance in the campaign, except for mobilizing specific districts, such as the large Cuban and Venezuelan communities in South Florida.
In such a context, it is difficult to gain public support for major reforms to the presidential election system or the way the government operates.
This situation is no different from the reform of the United Nations Security Council.
Many people believe that the current system has serious flaws and lacks representation, but it is impossible to reach a consensus on reform because any potential solution would benefit some people while harming others.
It is no surprise that those who will suffer losses from change will resist it.
This will make governance difficult.
To a large extent, this depends on Mitch McConnell, the Republican leader of the Senate, and his capacity and willingness to collaborate with the future President Biden.
Collaboration also requires Biden to make compromises, which is sure to face resistance from members within his party who are strongly ideologically driven.
Democrats once tried to sharply negate everything that Trump and his representatives stood for.
But they were not successful.
Republicans are seeking an election that would recognize Trump.
But this didn't go as they had hoped.
In contrast, elections reveal a country and two types of citizens.
They will have to coexist; but whether they can coexist remains to be seen.
